No P0 consensus defect found. The settled three-Book architecture holds: Book I remains unreachable from federation, Book II `interfere()` is still structural only, and Book III's selection-only F1-strict mechanics match the oracle and vectors in the code I ran.

The release is not hygiene-clean. I found one P1 CI gating bug that can make the federation second-implementation step go green despite a failed replay/differential command, plus several P2 stale-reference and precision defects. The new Lean accounting model is faithful to Book I §3.4 for the memory invariant, including the `R-K` discarded-argument minimum, but the bridge script checks the sufficient `growth < cost` premise, not a one-to-one classification of the seven Lean rows against runtime steps.

